'''Toyota Shrine''' (豊田神社) is a Shinto shrine located in Higashi-Mizue, Edogawa City, Tokyo.

== History ==
The exact date of the shrine's establishment is unknown. Originally named "Shimmeisha," it served as the guardian deity of {{ill|Shimokamata Village|ja|下鎌田村|12=draft}}.<ref name="Historical Walk">Uchida Sadao, ''Edo River Ward Historical Walk'' (Tokyo Historical Guide 23), Gakuseisha, 1992, pp. 89–90.</ref>{{sfn|江戸川区史}}.

During the [[Meiji period]]'s {{ill|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}} policy, the shrine's affiliated {{ill|Bettō|ja|別当寺|12=draft}}, Chōju-in Temple, was abolished, and the shrine was moved to the temple's former grounds and renamed "Toyota Shrine."<ref name="Historical Walk"/> {{sfn|江戸川区史}}.

The shrine precincts include the {{ill|Fuji mound|ja|富士塚|12=draft}} known as "Shimokamata no Fujizuka," which was constructed in 1916 by the {{ill|Fujikō|ja|富士講|12=draft}} group, "Shimokamata Waribishi Hakkō-kō." The mound is registered as a tangible cultural asset of Edogawa City.<ref name="Historical Walk"/> {{sfn|江戸川区 下鎌田の富士塚}}.

== Cultural Properties ==
* '''Toyota Shrine Forest''' - Designated as a natural monument of Edogawa City on February 8, 1982.{{sfn|江戸川区 豊田神社の社叢}}
* '''Shimokamata Fujizuka''' - Registered as a tangible folk cultural property of Edogawa City on March 15, 1983.{{sfn|江戸川区 下鎌田の富士塚}}

== Access ==
* 7-minute walk from {{ill|Mizue Station|ja|瑞江駅|12=draft}}. {{OSM経路図|start=35.69304,139.89765|goal=35.68944,139.89882|name=Route Map}}.

