'''Toyota Shrine''' (豊田神社) is a Shinto shrine located in Higashi-Mizue, Edogawa City, Tokyo.
== History == The exact date of the shrine's establishment is unknown. Originally named "Shimmeisha," it served as the guardian deity of {{ill|Shimokamata Village|ja|下鎌田村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimokamata Village|qq=}}.<ref name="Historical Walk">Uchida Sadao, ''Edo River Ward Historical Walk'' (Tokyo Historical Guide 23), Gakuseisha, 1992, pp. 89–90.</ref>{{sfn|江戸川区史}}.
During the [[Meiji period]]'s [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism]] policy, the shrine's affiliated {{ill|Bettō|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō|qq=}}, Chōju-in Temple, was abolished, and the shrine was moved to the temple's former grounds and renamed "Toyota Shrine."<ref name="Historical Walk"/> {{sfn|江戸川区史}}.
The shrine precincts include the [[:en:Fujizuka|Fuji mound]] known as "Shimokamata no Fujizuka," which was constructed in 1916 by the [[:en:Fujiko (religion)|Fujikō]] group, "Shimokamata Waribishi Hakkō-kō." The mound is registered as a tangible cultural asset of Edogawa City.<ref name="Historical Walk"/> {{sfn|江戸川区 下鎌田の富士塚}}.
== Cultural Properties == * '''Toyota Shrine Forest''' - Designated as a natural monument of Edogawa City on February 8, 1982.{{sfn|江戸川区 豊田神社の社叢}} * '''Shimokamata Fujizuka''' - Registered as a tangible folk cultural property of Edogawa City on March 15, 1983.{{sfn|江戸川区 下鎌田の富士塚}}
